le of market failure. He argues that television violence, like pollution, generates negative externalities, defined as costs borne by others than those involved in the production activity. Broadcasters seeking to attract viewers may not fully bear the costs to society of their violent programming, if those costs include such factors as increased levels of aggression and crime in society. Hamilton goes on to say that the comparison to pollution remains relevant when considering how to deal with the problem. Approaches devised to control violent programming, such as restricting it to certain times and rating programs according to the violence they contain, have parallels in zoning and education policies designed to protect the environment. Hamilton examines in detail the microstructure of incentives that operate at every level of television broadcasting, from programming and advertising to viewer behavior, so that remedies can be devised to reduce violent programming without restricting broadcasters' right to compete.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aNasilje. 0aTelevision broadcastingxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aTelevizija. 0aViolence on television. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aAction film.  aAdult.  aAdvertising.  aAggression.  aAmerican Family Association.  aAuction.  aAudience measurement.  aBeakman's World.  aBrand.  aBroadcast network.  aBroadcast programming.  aBroadcast syndication.  aCable television.  aCalculation.  aChairman.  aChapter 2.  aChapter 6.  aChildren's Television Act.  aCinemax.  aCompetition.  aConsideration.  aConsumer.  aContent analysis.  aCost–benefit analysis.  aCrime Story (TV series).  aCrime statistics.  aCriticism.  aCustomer.  aDemography.  aDummy variable (statistics).  aEconom